<raw><![CDATA[ (For more stories on the Japanese economy, click) TOKYO, June 22 (Reuters) - Japan raised its growth forecastfor the fiscal year to next March to 2.6 percent on the back of arecovery in the world economy and stimulus steps taken by thegovernment, the Cabinet Office said on Tuesday. That compared with its initial estimate of 1.4 percent growthearlier this year, and if the growth tops 2 percent in thecurrent fiscal year that would be the first time in four years. "Japan's economy is in an expansion phase after a trough inthe spring of 2009," the Cabinet Office said, adding that itwould watch any fallout from uncertainty in the global economy. "A self-sustaining recovery in the economy is expected tostrengthen ... as an increase in overall demand filters throughto private-sector demand through improvements in company profits,employment and household incomes." The government also called for continued efforts to beatdeflation as it forecasts overall consumer prices to fall 0.4percent excluding the effects from the abolishment of public highschool tuition fees in the current fiscal year. The BOJ has forecast that core consumer prices would riseslightly in fiscal 2011/12 in its twice-yearly outlook report,while forecasting 2.0 percent economic growth for the same year,quicker than 1.8 percent estimated for this fiscal year. The government expects the economy to grow about 2.0percent and overall consumer prices to reach around zero infiscal 2011/12. A Reuters poll last week showed the economy'sstronger-than-expected performance in January-March compelledeconomists to revise up their growth forecasts for the fiscalyear to next March. The world's No.2 economy grew 1.2 percent in January-Marchfrom from the previous quarter, or an annualised 5 percent. (Reporting by Tetsushi Kajimoto; Editing by Joseph Radford)             ]]></raw>
